Ahhh got ityep, that explains it perfectly. If Cloudflares bot fight mode, firewall rules, or bot protection headers are still active, theyll block most verification requests from search engines and external preview tools like mine.

Heres the quick checklist to fully un-gag the site for both humans and crawlers:

Cloudflare Anti-Crawler / Bot Settings to Disable

Inside your Cloudflare dashboard:

1. Bot Fight Mode

  • Go to: Security > Bots
  • Toggle OFF Bot Fight Mode
  • This is the most common one breaking GitHub Pages and Dev URLs

2. WAF (Web Application Firewall) Rules

  • Go to: Security > WAF > Custom Rules
  • Delete or disable any rules blocking user agents, search engine bots, or "empty referrers"

3. Browser Integrity Check

  • Go to: Security > Settings
  • Turn off Browser Integrity Check

4. Challenge JavaScript / Captchas

  • Under Security > Access Rules, remove any JS challenge or CAPTCHA rules that are region-wide or IP-based

Bonus Tips:

  • Purge Cache after you disable settings (Caching > Configuration > Purge Everything)
  • Re-test with private/incognito window or bot preview tools like Google Rich Results Test
  • Set your Pages site to Always Online under Caching > Always Online

Once you unlock those settings, your .pages.dev site should:

  • Load properly from anywhere
  • Be crawlable by search engines
  • Be accessible by tools like mine or headless browser agents

Where do I place my robots.txr

2025-07-30T06:05:27.178279Z assistant

To properly configure a robots.txt file for your Cloudflare Pages site (e.g. everlight-restore-page.pages.dev), follow this simple setup:

1. Create Your robots.txt File

In the root directory of your GitHub repo (where index.html lives), add a plain text file named:

robots.txt

Example contents:

User-agent: *
Allow: /

This allows all bots to crawl everything. You can adjust this if needed (e.g., disallow certain paths).

2. Commit and Push to GitHub

Once your robots.txt is in the root directory, commit it:

git add robots.txt
git commit -m "Add robots.txt"
git push origin main

3. Confirm Its Live

After deployment, visit:

https://everlight-restore-page.pages.dev/robots.txt

It should render your file as plain text. If it doesnt:

  • Double check that robots.txt is at the root, not in a subfolder
  • Make sure the deployment finished without errors
  • Clear your Cloudflare cache if you recently purged other settings

Important Notes

  • If youre using a custom domain (e.g. returnofthebirdtribes.com), the robots.txt should still be served from https://yourdomain.com/robots.txt once mapped correctly.
  • GitHub Pages will serve the file automatically if it's in the repo root.
  • Cloudflare wont block it unless you have active WAF or cache rules that interfere.
